<?xml-stylesheet type="text/xsl" href="../assets/xml/rss.xsl" media="all"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Lacking Natural Simplicity (Posts about kane)</title><link>https://tkurtbond.github.io/</link><description></description><atom:link href="https://tkurtbond.github.io/categories/kane.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><language>en</language><copyright>Contents © 2024 &lt;a href="mailto:tkurtbond@gmail.com"&gt;T. Kurt Bond&lt;/a&gt; </copyright><lastBuildDate>Mon, 22 Jan 2024 04:12:56 GMT</lastBuildDate><generator>Nikola (getnikola.com)</generator><docs>http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/tech/rss</docs><item><title>Karl Edward Wagner's Horror Stories</title><link>https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/12/karl-edward-wagners-horror-stories/</link><dc:creator>T. Kurt Bond</dc:creator><description>&lt;p&gt;I primarily know &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Edward_Wagner"&gt;Karl Edward Wagner&lt;/a&gt;'s work from his “heroic
fantasy” &lt;a class="footnote-reference brackets" href="https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/12/karl-edward-wagners-horror-stories/#hf" id="footnote-reference-1" role="doc-noteref"&gt;&lt;span class="fn-bracket"&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;1&lt;span class="fn-bracket"&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt; novels and stories of &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Edward_Wagner#Kane,_the_Mystic_Swordsman"&gt;Kane&lt;/a&gt; which I picked up in
paperback in the mid 1980s, but he was equally talented as a writer
and editor of horror.  I &lt;em&gt;have&lt;/em&gt; read his British Fantasy Award-winning
story &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20110708122112/http://www.thecimmerian.com/the-terror-of-the-absurd-karl-edward-wagners-sticks/"&gt;Sticks&lt;/a&gt; and it had a considerable effect on me, but I don't
remember every reading any of his other horror stories.  The &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.isfdb.org/"&gt;ISFDB&lt;/a&gt;
has what seems a very complete &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/ea.cgi?153"&gt;page&lt;/a&gt; listing his writings.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I aim to fix that.  I've now got copies of the &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centipede_Press"&gt;Centipede Press&lt;/a&gt;
collections &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/pl.cgi?372768"&gt;Where the Summer Ends&lt;/a&gt; (2012) and &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/pl.cgi?372769"&gt;Walk on the Wild
Side&lt;/a&gt; (2012) and I'll be reading them soon.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;aside class="footnote-list brackets"&gt;
&lt;aside class="footnote brackets" id="hf" role="doc-footnote"&gt;
&lt;span class="label"&gt;&lt;span class="fn-bracket"&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;&lt;a role="doc-backlink" href="https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/12/karl-edward-wagners-horror-stories/#footnote-reference-1"&gt;1&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span class="fn-bracket"&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A term he vastly preferred to “Sword &amp;amp; Sorcery”.  Or maybe he
&lt;a class="reference external" href="https://thesilverkey.blogspot.com/2019/10/remembering-karl-edward-wagner-1945-1994.html"&gt;preferred&lt;/a&gt; (note 1 at the bottom of the post) “epic fantasy” or
“dark fantasy”.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/aside&gt;
&lt;/aside&gt;</description><category>dark fantasy</category><category>epic fantasy</category><category>fiction</category><category>heroic fantasy</category><category>horror</category><category>kane</category><category>karl edward wagner</category><category>sword &amp; sorcery</category><guid>https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/12/karl-edward-wagners-horror-stories/</guid><pubDate>Thu, 12 Mar 2020 19:35:02 GMT</pubDate></item><item><title>Dale E. Rippke's Kane Timeline &amp; Reflections on Planned but Unfinished Novels</title><link>https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/12/dale-e-rippkes-kane-timeline-reflections-on-planned-but-unfinished-novels/</link><dc:creator>T. Kurt Bond</dc:creator><description>&lt;p&gt;Dale E. Rippke over at the &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://thedarkstormfiles.blogspot.com/"&gt;The Darkstorm Files&lt;/a&gt; has a wonderful
timeline, &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://thedarkstormfiles.blogspot.com/2011/12/lord-of-chaos.html"&gt;Lord of Chaos&lt;/a&gt;, of Kane's adventures.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;He also has two interesting articles on the planned but unfinished
Kane novels, &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://thedarkstormfiles.blogspot.com/2011/12/reflections-of-midnight-sun-by-dale.html"&gt;Reflections of a Midnight Sun&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://thedarkstormfiles.blogspot.com/2011/12/phantasmal-tomes-by-dale-e.html"&gt;Phantasmal Tomes&lt;/a&gt;,
and another interesting article on the Kane/Elric crossover,
&lt;a class="reference external" href="http://thedarkstormfiles.blogspot.com/2011/12/rethinking-gothic-touch.html"&gt;Rethinking The Gothic Touch&lt;/a&gt;, and a world gazetteer of Kane, &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://thedarkstormfiles.blogspot.com/2015/12/the-age-of-shattered-empires.html"&gt;The Age of
Shattered Empires&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There is a &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-ID-4IjCaXow/U8x0X2HHe7I/AAAAAAAAByI/85ODFbkJSBg/s1600/Kane-Map.jpg"&gt;map&lt;/a&gt; of Kane's world (pinterest tells me that site is
banned because it “leads to spam”) which I gather was drawn after
Dale E. Rippke's original, which I can find no trace of on the
Internet.  I did find his original Kane &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20091127065103/http://home.mchsi.com/~moonblossom/kane.htm"&gt;page&lt;/a&gt; on &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://archive.org/"&gt;archive.org&lt;/a&gt;, but
sadly none of the linked pages was saved by archive.org.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;And I stumbled over the post &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://sorcerersskull.blogspot.com/2010/02/gaming-kane.html"&gt;Gaming Kane&lt;/a&gt; at &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://sorcerersskull.blogspot.com/"&gt;From The Sorcerer's
Skull&lt;/a&gt; which gives some information about Kane in &lt;cite&gt;Dragon Magazine&lt;/cite&gt;
#26 (June 1979) as a D&amp;amp;D character.&lt;/p&gt;</description><category>dale e. rippke</category><category>kane</category><category>kane timeline</category><category>karl edward wagner</category><category>planned kane novels</category><guid>https://tkurtbond.github.io/posts/2020/03/12/dale-e-rippkes-kane-timeline-reflections-on-planned-but-unfinished-novels/</guid><pubDate>Thu, 12 Mar 2020 15:25:53 GMT</pubDate></item></channel></rss>